See http://infinitemonkeycorps.net/docs/pph/#id9
for info on how to create a python project

See http://infinitemonkeycorps.net/docs/pph/#unittesting
for info on how to write doctests and unittests,
how to write docummentation, and more.

Tip: Use the pyreverse program (part of pylint) to generate the diagram of
classes and packages (in dot format).

Put README info here. It should have
 - Name, version, and release date of the package
 - Brief description of the package
 - Any dependencies or required versions of Python
 - How to install the package (ideally just easy_install packagename)
 - How to run the program(s), if your package contains scripts
 - Package author and contact information
 - Copyright and licensing terms
 - Pointer to full documentation


Useful functions in numpy
http://www.scipy.org/Tentative_NumPy_Tutorial
 - vstack, hstack, dstack (tb pode usar concatenate), row_stack, column_stack
 - vsplit, hsplit, dsplit
 - aprenda a usar "view"
   Ex: a = array([1,2,3,4])
       b = a.view()
       b.shape = (2,2)  -> NÃ£o muda "a"
 - bmat
 - newaxis -> a[np.newaxis,:,:] adiciona um novo axis como o primeiro axis
 - automatic reshape -> a = arange(30); a.shape = 2,-1,3 # -1 means
                                                         # "whatever is needed"
 - linalg.diagsvd

Note que vstack e hstack criam um novo array (matriz) independente dos
arrays usados, mas vsplit e hsplit criam slices dos arrays originais.
